                },
                {
                    "id": "69c55f97cf4290a8d4e6e002",
                    "text": "Technical Challenges",
                    "blockName": null,
                    "blockType": "heading"
                },
                {
                    "id": "69c55f9dcf4290a8d4e6e004",
                    "text": {
                        "root": {
                            "children": [
                                {
                                    "children": [
                                        {
                                            "detail": 0,
                                            "format": 0,
                                            "mode": "normal",
                                            "style": "",
                                            "text": "To create Xenoplanet’s infinite world new chunks have to constantly be loaded around the player, and there are two major challenges I had to overcome to achieve this. Firstly, the computation time needed to generate the noise maps and mesh data for a chunk are greater than the length of a frame, causing stuttering when new chunks are generated. Secondly, Unity's `instantiate` method is slow and impractical for placing the amount of objects we’ll need to place so we have to find a work around that avoids calling the method.",
                                            "type": "text",
                                            "version": 1
                                        }
                                    ],
                                    "direction": null,
                                    "format": "",
                                    "indent": 0,
                                    "type": "paragraph",
                                    "version": 1,
                                    "textFormat": 0,
                                    "textStyle": ""
                                }
                            ],
                            "direction": null,
                            "format": "",
                            "indent": 0,
                            "type": "root",
                            "version": 1
                        }
                    },
                    "blockName": null,
                    "blockType": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                    "id": "69c55fa1cf4290a8d4e6e006",
                    "text": "Computation",
                    "blockName": null,
                    "blockType": "subheading"
                },
                {
                    "id": "69c55fa9cf4290a8d4e6e008",
                    "text": {
                        "root": {
                            "children": [
                                {
                                    "children": [
                                        {
                                            "detail": 0,
                                            "format": 0,
                                            "mode": "normal",
                                            "style": "",
                                            "text": "CPUs are extremely fast but they can generally only do one thing at a time. This causes problems for us when we want to do large calculations, like the generation of a noise map, because the CPU has to finish the entire calculation before it can move on to rendering the next frame of our game. When the CPU isn't ready to start rendering the next frame in time the player experiences lag.",
                                            "type": "text",
                                            "version": 1
                                        }
                                    ],
                                    "direction": null,
                                    "format": "",
                                    "indent": 0,
                                    "type": "paragraph",
                                    "version": 1,
                                    "textFormat": 0,
                                    "textStyle": ""
                                }
                            ],
                            "direction": null,
                            "format": "",
                            "indent": 0,
                            "type": "root",
                            "version": 1
                        }
                    },
                    "blockName": null,
                    "blockType": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                    "id": "69c55fb4cf4290a8d4e6e00a",
                    "text": {
                        "root": {
                            "children": [
                                {
                                    "children": [
                                        {
                                            "detail": 0,
                                            "format": 0,
                                            "mode": "normal",
                                            "style": "",
                                            "text": "If we’re trying to hit a target of 60 fps we have 16.6ms to get all our calculations done before the next frame. And our main game loop and rendering may only take 2-6ms, leaving us with more than 10ms of extra time each frame. This might not seem like much, but that’s more than half a second of free computation for every second that passes in the game! I was able to leverage this extra time by breaking up large calculations into smaller chunks that run during this extra time. Now a calculation that may have taken longer than a frame can still be performed without the player noticing any lag!",
                                            "type": "text",
                                            "version": 1
                                        }
                                    ],
                                    "direction": null,
                                    "format": "",
                                    "indent": 0,
                                    "type": "paragraph",
                                    "version": 1,
                                    "textFormat": 0,
                                    "textStyle": ""
                                }
                            ],
                            "direction": null,
                            "format": "",
                            "indent": 0,
                            "type": "root",
                            "version": 1
                        }
                    },
                    "blockName": null,
                    "blockType": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                    "id": "69c55fc8cf4290a8d4e6e010",
                    "text": "Instantiation",
                    "blockName": null,
                    "blockType": "subheading"
                },
                {
                    "id": "69c55fbacf4290a8d4e6e00c",
                    "text": {
                        "root": {
                            "children": [
                                {
                                    "children": [
                                        {
                                            "detail": 0,
                                            "format": 0,
                                            "mode": "normal",
                                            "style": "",
                                            "text": "Each chunk in Xenoplanet needed to be populated with 4096 grass objects placed at specific heights and orientations. Unfortunately, Unity’s Instantiate method, used to create new objects, is notoriously slow. This created a unique challenge, as even if I broke up the grass instantiation over multiple frames it would take an impractical amount of time, more than the extra time we have available each frame.",
                                            "type": "text",
                                            "version": 1
                                        }
                                    ],
                                    "direction": null,
                                    "format": "",
                                    "indent": 0,
                                    "type": "paragraph",
                                    "version": 1,
                                    "textFormat": 0,
                                    "textStyle": ""
                                }
                            ],
                            "direction": null,
                            "format": "",
                            "indent": 0,
                            "type": "root",
                            "version": 1
                        }
                    },
                    "blockName": null,
                    "blockType": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                    "id": "69c55fc2cf4290a8d4e6e00e",
                    "text": {
                        "root": {
                            "children": [
                                {
                                    "children": [
                                        {
                                            "detail": 0,
                                            "format": 0,
                                            "mode": "normal",
                                            "style": "",
                                            "text": "The solution I found for this was to use object pooling. Rather than instantiating a new set of grass on each chunk I loaded the scene with 25 objects, each containing one set of 4096 grass objects. I could then reuse these 25 objects by moving them to the 5x5 area of chunks closed to the player. This achieved the effect of making the infinite world seem covered in grass without ever having to use Unitie’s instantiate method.",
                                            "type": "text",
                                            "version": 1
                                        }
                                    ],
                                    "direction": null,
                                    "format": "",
                                    "indent": 0,
                                    "type": "paragraph",
                                    "version": 1,
                                    "textFormat": 0,
                                    "textStyle": ""
                                }
                            ],
                            "direction": null,
                            "format": "",
                            "indent": 0,
                            "type": "root",
                            "version": 1
                        }
                    },
                    "blockName": null,
                    "blockType": "paragraph"
                }
            ],
